00:27:30,078 --> 00:27:31,879
and they'll just be nothing but trees

562
00:27:33,440 --> 00:27:34,900
he'll run about 2 frames per second.

563
00:27:38,781 --> 00:27:40,641
I think one of the things with procedural generation

564
00:27:40,661 --> 00:27:43,982
that I found really, really exciting is that

565
00:27:44,742 --> 00:27:47,043
I've been working in games for a long time

566
00:27:47,083 --> 00:27:49,043
where tools are so amazing now

567
00:27:49,123 --> 00:27:50,403
but they still feel really

568
00:27:51,684 --> 00:27:53,744
arduous. It still feels like a real slog

569
00:27:53,804 --> 00:27:55,205
to get to where you want to get.

570
00:27:55,265 --> 00:27:56,105
You're still having to

571
00:27:57,345 --> 00:28:00,026
load up ZBrush, transfer maps,

572
00:28:00,106 --> 00:28:01,246
blah, blah, blah, all this kind of thing.

573
00:28:02,773 --> 00:28:04,755
And it feels like there's more and more tools now

574
00:28:04,775 --> 00:28:07,777
that are starting to enable procedural technology,

575
00:28:07,797 --> 00:28:11,000
like the Quixel Suite, Speedtree, and Substance Design,

576
00:28:11,060 --> 00:28:14,564
and they're kind of avoiding all these pointlessly

577
00:28:15,645 --> 00:28:17,927
long, drawn-out processes where we can just get,

578
00:28:18,667 --> 00:28:21,210
we can get results without having to hand draw

579
00:28:21,270 --> 00:28:22,971
and jump through all these technical hoops.

